div.div:
Horizontal dotted lines represent version boundaries that must not be merged.
Reason: Each transaction must check for conflicts in commit versions newer than its snapshot. This check must not read into the original snapshot; or else false conflicts can be detected.
1. While a transaction establishes its initial snapshot, it holds the snapshot's upper boundary.
1. While a transaction checks for conflicts, it holds the snapshot's both upper and lower boundaries, and releases any prior boundary.
1. When a transaction finishes, it unholds all its remaining held boundaries.

div.div:
Linked list design considerations
Operations on the linked list:
By many
transactions
:
Get one key-value entry => Read newest-to-older.
Get range of key-value entries => Read in either direction.
Check conflicts => Read the slice between the previously held snapshot and the newest end of the LL, in either direction.
Commit => Push a node at the newest end.
By one
F+C
job:
Read in either direction.
Replace a slice with a node, somewhere in the list.
By one
SICr
job:
Read a snapshot, in either direction.
Insert a node, somewhere in the snapshot.
Singly-linked vs doubly-linked:
Newer-to-older traversal is needed.
Older-to-newer traversal is optional.
It allows for a more flexible design of the F+C job algo.
E.g. it is possible to maintain a boundary across which all older nodes are SSTables and all newer nodes are MemLogs.
One benefit from this is that k-merging uses simpler types. We need one k-merged iterator for SSTables and one ditto for SSTables, and merge these two. But it's possible to work around this, so this is low-priority.
MemLog --> Iterator< Item = (&K, &OptDatum<V>) >
SSTable --> Iterator< Item = Result<(K, OptDatum<V>)> >
